  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "Extensor Zone III Injury over the PIP joint.\nMost commonly central tendon is injured, causing FDS to be unopposed, thus causing flexion of PIP\nDisruption of central tendon causes lateral bands to be displaced volarly, causing them to act like flexors\nFDP still intact",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "History of trauma to digit and painful PIP.\nForced flexion of actively extended finger\nDirect blow to PIP\nJamming\nLaceration distal to PIP can injure central tendon\nOn exam, will see hyperflexion of PIP with hyperextension of DIP and MP joints.",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Differential_Diagnosis": {
      "text": "Rheumatoid arthritis\nVolar\nPIP dislocation\nFlexion contracture of PIP joint",
